# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: covington-kentucky
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The **119th United States Congress** is the current meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened on January 3, 2025, for the last 17 days of Joe Biden's presidency and continued during the first two years of Donald Trump's second presidency.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Following the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained its slim majority in the House of Representatives (albeit with losing two net seats to end up with a three-seat majority).
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Republican Party also won a three-seat majority in the Senate after winning four net seats.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Upon Trump's second inauguration on January 20, 2025, the Republican Party has an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 115th Congress (2017–2019), which was in session during Trump's first term.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The 119th Congress features the slimmest majority in the House for any party since the 72nd Congress (1931–1933), and the first openly transgender member of Congress in history, Representative Sarah McBride (D-DE).
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] It also features the fewest split Senate delegations since the passage of the Seventeenth Amendment, which established the direct election of U.S. senators.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Despite a trifecta, the first year of the Congress saw the lowest number of House votes in a nonelection year since the 101st Congress in 1990.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In the 2024 elections, the Republican Party retained control of the House of Representatives and gained control of the Senate, while Republican nominee Donald Trump won the presidential election, securing a second non-consecutive term.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The results of the election were attributed to economic conditions of voters and concerns over immigration, particularly the Mexico–United States border crisis.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate flipped to a 53–47 Republican majority, and in their leadership elections, Senator John Thune of South Dakota was elected to succeed Mitch McConnell, who had been in power for 18 years.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The House assumed a 220–215 Republican majority, among the narrowest controlling majorities in House history with the 65th Congress.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] Mike Johnson was re-elected as speaker on the first ballot after initially not receiving enough votes on the roll call, with the vote remaining open until enough members changed votes to support him.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] On January 6, a joint session convened to count the presidential Electoral College votes.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The proceedings were peaceful, four years after the January 6 Capitol attack, in which supporters of Trump entered the Capitol and disrupted Joe Biden's certification as president.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In response to the attack and Trump's efforts to overturn the 2020 election, Congress has passed revisions to the Electoral Count Act that prevent the vice president from altering the results and significantly raises the bar for certification objections.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All class 1 seats were contested in the November 2024 elections.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] In this Congress, class 1 means their term commenced in the current Congress, requiring re-election in 2030; class 2 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2026; and class 3 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2028.
[src:covington-kentucky/119th-united-states-congress-p01] All seats were filled by election in November 2024, or special elections thereafter as noted below.
[src:covington-kentucky/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:covington-kentucky/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:covington-kentucky/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:covington-kentucky/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:covington-kentucky/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:covington-kentucky/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:covington-kentucky/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:covington-kentucky/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:covington-kentucky/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:covington-kentucky/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:covington-kentucky/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In 1814, John Gano, Richard Gano, and Thomas Carneal purchased The Point, 150 acres (0.6 km2) of land on the west side of the Licking River at its confluence with the Ohio, from Thomas Kennedy for $50,000, and laid out the settlement of Covington the next year.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Leonard Covington, who was killed at the Battle of Crysler's Farm during the War of 1812.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The town was formally incorporated by the Kentucky General Assembly a year later and raised to city status in 1834.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The city prospered as an emporium for Kentucky's tobacco and cigar production.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In 1862, Stewart Iron Works was established; for a time, it was the largest iron fence maker in the world and still exists today as part of the Huseman Group of Cincinnati.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] There were also distilleries, glassworks, and stove factories.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Like nearby Cincinnati, Covington's factories and businesses were particularly staffed by Catholic and German immigrants.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Its Catholic church was eventually raised to the level of a diocese.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The city was determined as the center of the country's population by the U.S.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] By 1900, Covington was the second-largest city and industrial region in Kentucky.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] At the time, its population of almost 43,000 was about 12% foreign-born and 5% Black.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] By this time, it was connected to the Chesapeake & Ohio and Louisville & Nashville railways, and companies offered steamboat service to other ports on the Ohio River.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Its factories had expanded to include cotton goods, machinery, and cordage.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington even boasted a Federal League baseball team, the Covington Blue Sox, during the 1913 season.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The present-day circuit courthouse is located at the site of its former grounds, Federal Park, which is thought to have been the smallest stadium ever used by a professional baseball club.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] It declined in importance during the Great Depression and the middle 20th century.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The city has undergone some redevelopment during the late 20th and early 21st centuries as the most populous city in Kenton County.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Covington Police Department has been sued 14 times in federal court since 2021. with half of those lawsuits involving the conduct of a single officer, Doug Ullrich.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The city is on the south bank of the Ohio River with Cincinnati, Ohio across the river to the north.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Licking River forms the eastern boundary with Newport in the adjacent Campbell County.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] According to the United States Census Bureau, Covington has a total area of 13.7 square miles (35 km2), of which 13.1 square miles (34 km2) is land and 0.5 square miles (1.3 km2) (3.88%) is covered by water.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington claims 19 distinct neighborhoods, ranging in population from several hundred to 10,000 people.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Many of the neighborhoods are located in 12 historic districts that are predominantly found in the northern portion of the city, but Covington annexed many areas to the south in the late 20th and early 21st centuries to significantly enlarge its land area.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Most of the neighborhoods have active resident associations or block watches that are dedicated to involving residents in strengthening their neighborhoods and improving safety, housing, and beautification.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington is located within a climatic transition zone; it is nestled within the southern end of the humid continental climate zone and the northern periphery of the humid subtropical climate of the Upland South, with hot, humid summers and cool winters.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] As of the 2020 census, Covington had a population of 40,961 and a population density of 3,103.8 people per square mile (1,198.4/km2).
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The median age was 35.7 years; 22.1% of residents were under the age of 18, 64.6% were 18 to 64, and 13.3% were 65 years of age or older.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] For every 100 females there were 98.7 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 97.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] 99.8% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.2% lived in rural areas.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] There were 18,099 households, of which 24.6% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Of all households, 27.7% were married-couple households, 27.3% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 34.3% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] About 40.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The average household size was 2.21 and the average family size was 2.99.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] There were 20,576 housing units, of which 12.0% were vacant.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.6%.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Census American Community Survey, for the period 2016-2020 the estimated median annual income for a household in the city was $47,917, and the median income for a family was $60,224.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] About 23.9% of the population were living below the poverty line, including 37.9% of those under age 18 and 14.6% of those age 65 or over.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] About 61.8% of the population were employed.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] As of the census of 2000, 43,370 people, 18,257 households, and 10,132 families resided in the city.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The population density was 3,301.3 inhabitants per square mile (1,274.6/km2).
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The racial makeup of the city was 87.05% White, 10.14% African American, 0.24% Native American, 0.34% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.63% from other races, and 1.57% from two or more races.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Hispanics or Latinos of any race were 1.38% of the population.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The average household size was 2.31 and the average family size was 3.08.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] For every 100 females, there were 95.9 males.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 92.0 males.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The median income for a household in the city was $30,735, and the median income for a family was $38,307.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Males had a median income of $31,238 versus $24,487 for females.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The per capita income for the city was $16,841.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] About 15.5% of families and 18.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 25.0% of those under age 18 and 13.4% of those age 65 or over.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington has some of the least expensive real estate in Kentucky; the median house price in Covington is around $95,430, while the median house price for Kentucky as a whole is $124,100.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In September 2025, the new four-story, OneNKY Center, office and lab facility had its grand opening.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The main tenant being LifeSciKY, which will operate a, $15 million, 15,000-sq-ft facility specializing in biotech lab and incubator within the center.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington has five churches listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Mary's Cathedral Basilica of the Assumption is a minor basilica under the Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] It was built in 1895 and is famous for what is said to be the world's largest handmade church stained glass window, at 67 ft × 24 ft (20.4 m × 7.3 m).
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Mother of God Roman Catholic Church is a historic German church built in 1869 and included in the Mutter Gottes Historic District.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The church features twin renaissance towers and murals by Vatican artist Johann Schmitt.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Augustine Church Complex is another German parish constructed in 1913.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Holy Cross Church and School Complex-Latonia was constructed between 1906 and 1908 with the elementary school added in 1914, rectory in 1924, the high school in 1930 and the convent in 1941.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Trinity Episcopal Church was constructed between 1857 and 1859.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Daniel Carter Beard Boyhood Home is a National Historic Landmark located in the Riverside Drive Historic District.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The home was built in 1821 and is one of the two oldest buildings in Kenton County.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Daniel Carter Beard, a founder of the Boy Scouts of America, grew up here in the mid-19th century.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Public education within much of Covington is provided by Covington Independent Public Schools, the largest independent school district in Kentucky.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Its high school, Holmes Junior/Senior High School, is the oldest public high school in the state.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Southern portions of the city are in the Kenton County School District.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Roman Catholic Diocese of Covington operates two high schools in the city, Covington Latin School and Holy Cross High School.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Two Catholic high schools, the all-boys' Covington Catholic High School and all-girls' Notre Dame Academy, moved to neighboring Park Hills in the 1950s.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Calvary Christian School, a Baptist school, is also located in Covington.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Kentucky Educational Television station for Northern Kentucky, WCVN-TV (channel 54), is licensed to Covington, along with gospel station WCVG (1320 AM).
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Route 25, Interstate 71 and Interstate 75 serve downtown Covington.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Bus transit is served by the Transit Authority of Northern Kentucky (TANK).
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington Union Station served Chesapeake and Ohio and Louisville and Nashville passenger trains into the 1960s.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The final train making stops at the station was the L&N's *Pan-American* (Cincinnati-New Orleans) in 1971.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The L&N's *Humming Bird* (Cincinnati- Memphis and New Orleans) also served the station.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] C&O trains included the *Fast Flying Virginian,* *George Washington* and *Sportsman.* The C&O dropped Union Station from its trains' itineraries in 1966.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington is served by Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport (CVG), which is the largest airport in the state.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The airport is one of DHL Aviation's three superhubs, serving destinations throughout the Americas, Europe, Africa, and Asia, making it the fifth-busiest airport in the U.S. based on cargo operations.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] CVG also serves as a focus city for Allegiant Air and is the airline's largest O&D airport.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The airport additionally serves as an operating base for Delta Air Lines subsidiary Endeavor Air and Frontier Airlines as well as a maintenance base for American Airlines subsidiary PSA Airlines.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In January 2026, Minneapolis–based Sun Country Airlines opened an operating base at the airport.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The 1936 Licking River Bridge, the main connector between Covington and Newport, is scheduled to be torn down and replaced.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Starting in the spring of 2026, the Licking River Bridge, will be demolished and rebuilt over a two-year construction period.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The new bridge is expected to open in the summer of 2028.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The 12th Street Bridge will temporarily become the main connector between Covington and Newport.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In late 2022, funding was settled for the Brent Spence Bridge Corridor Project, which will construct a new double-deck companion bridge to carry interstate through-traffic, while the existing Brent Spence Bridge will be reconfigured for local traffic only, through Cincinnati and Covington.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Approximately eight miles of improved roadways spanning Kentucky and Ohio will be constructed.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The total project cost is estimated at $3.6 billion, and a federal grant of $1.6 billion was awarded in late 2022 to the project, with the remaining cost evenly split between Ohio and Kentucky.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Major construction is expected to begin in 2026.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In 1817, the Town of Covington created the position "Captain of Patrol", and assigned two "Patrollers" under his supervision.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The patrol area included the Town and eight miles of surrounding territory.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In 1833 the first full time Town Marshall was appointed.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] An act of the Kentucky General Assembly in 1834 incorporated Covington as a city, and in 1842, the City of Covington appointed its first "Police Commissioner".
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington City Ordinance created the "Voluntary Night Watch" in 1843, which consisted of seventy-one reputable persons invested with police authority.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] In 1856 a regular citizen's police force was established.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The department is staffed by 114 sworn officers, each assigned to one of 4 bureaus.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] There are substations, and a central headquarters.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The department maintains accreditation through the Kentucky Association of Chiefs of Police as well as the Commission on Accreditation for Law Enforcement Agencies.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Covington Fire Department was created on June 30, 1864.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Since 1918, the Covington Fire Department has been represented by Covington Professional Firefighters Local 38, a member union of the International Association of Firefighters.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington FD was a charter member of the IAFF.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Ron Washington is currently the mayor of Covington, having been elected in 2024, after serving four years on the Covington Board of Commissioners.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Washington made history by being the first African-American mayor of Covington.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] Covington is served by a four-member Board of Commissioners.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The United States District Court for the Eastern District of Kentucky maintains a divisional office in Covington.
[src:covington-kentucky/covington-kentucky] The Kenton County Fiscal Court also maintains a courthouse in Covington, meeting every 4th Tuesday of the month.
